{"executive_summary":"Zero-downtime migration of the Order Management domain from MongoDB to PostgreSQL using a dual-write with change-data-capture (CDC) pattern. The architecture phases through four stages: (1) backfill historical data, (2) dual-write with PostgreSQL as secondary, (3) dual-read verification, (4) cutover with PostgreSQL as primary. At 200 writes/minute, the system is well within the throughput ceiling for either database, so the dominant risk is data consistency during the transition window, not performance.","architecture":{"components":[{"name":"Order Service (Application Layer)","responsibility":"Handles all order CRUD operations. During migration, contains a write-routing layer that controls which databases receive writes and which serve reads.","boundaries":"Owns all order and payment business logic. Does not leak database-specific concerns beyond the repository layer."},{"name":"Migration Orchestrator","responsibility":"Coordinates migration phases, tracks progress, exposes health endpoints, and provides rollback triggers. Runs as a sidecar or standalone service.","boundaries":"Stateless coordinator — reads migration state from a dedicated migration_state table in PostgreSQL. Does not process business logic."},{"name":"CDC Pipeline (Change Data Capture)","responsibility":"Tails the MongoDB oplog to capture all writes during migration and replays them to PostgreSQL, ensuring eventual consistency during the backfill phase.","boundaries":"Reads MongoDB oplog, transforms documents to relational rows, writes to PostgreSQL. Idempotent — safe to replay. Does not modify MongoDB."},{"name":"Backfill Worker","responsibility":"Batch-migrates the 8M historical order documents from MongoDB to PostgreSQL. Runs at a throttled rate to avoid impacting production traffic.","boundaries":"Read-only access to MongoDB. Write access to PostgreSQL. Processes in batches of 1000 with configurable parallelism and rate limiting."},{"name":"Consistency Verifier","responsibility":"Continuously samples records from both databases and compares them, reporting drift. Blocks cutover if drift exceeds threshold.","boundaries":"Read-only access to both databases. Writes verification results to a metrics/logging system."},{"name":"Feature Flag Controller","responsibility":"Controls which phase the migration is in (shadow-write, dual-read, cutover, rollback). Allows instant rollback without deployment.","boundaries":"Integrates with existing feature flag system or uses a simple config-driven approach."},{"name":"PostgreSQL Schema & Repository","responsibility":"Relational schema for orders, order_items, payments, and related tables. Repository implementation behind the same interface as the MongoDB repository.","boundaries":"Owns the relational model. Exposed only through the OrderRepository interface."},{"name":"MongoDB Repository (Legacy)","responsibility":"Existing MongoDB-backed repository. Remains active as fallback until migration is fully complete and verified.","boundaries":"Read/write during early phases, read-only during verification phase, fully decommissioned post-cutover."}],"interfaces":[{"from":"Order Service","to":"MongoDB Repository","contract":"OrderRepository interface — findById, save, update, delete, query methods. Identical interface shared with PostgreSQL repository.","coupling_type":"loose (interface-based, swappable)"},{"from":"Order Service","to":"PostgreSQL Schema & Repository","contract":"Same OrderRepository interface. Implementations are swapped via the Feature Flag Controller.","coupling_type":"loose (interface-based, swappable)"},{"from":"Order Service","to":"Feature Flag Controller","contract":"getPhase() returns current migration phase enum: MONGO_PRIMARY, DUAL_WRITE, DUAL_READ, PG_PRIMARY, COMPLETE","coupling_type":"loose (read-only config)"},{"from":"CDC Pipeline","to":"MongoDB Repository","contract":"Tails oplog via MongoDB Change Streams API. Reads insert/update/delete events.","coupling_type":"tight (MongoDB-specific, temporary)"},{"from":"CDC Pipeline","to":"PostgreSQL Schema & Repository","contract":"Upserts transformed relational rows. Uses idempotent write operations keyed on order_id + version.","coupling_type":"moderate (schema-aware, temporary)"},{"from":"Backfill Worker","to":"MongoDB Repository","contract":"Paginated batch reads using _id cursor. Read-only.","coupling_type":"moderate (temporary)"},{"from":"Backfill Worker","to":"PostgreSQL Schema & Repository","contract":"Batch upserts with conflict resolution on order_id.","coupling_type":"moderate (temporary)"},{"from":"Consistency Verifier","to":"Both Repositories","contract":"Read-only sampling queries. Compares record counts, checksums, and spot-check field values.","coupling_type":"loose (read-only)"},{"from":"Migration Orchestrator","to":"Feature Flag Controller","contract":"Advances phase when verification thresholds are met. Can trigger rollback.","coupling_type":"moderate (control plane)"}],"data_flow":"Phase 1 (Backfill): Backfill Worker reads MongoDB in batches → transforms documents to relational rows → upserts into PostgreSQL. CDC Pipeline runs concurrently, tailing oplog for any writes that occur during backfill → applies them to PostgreSQL. Deduplication via order_id + updated_at version ensures idempotency. Phase 2 (Dual-Write): Order Service writes to MongoDB first (primary), then synchronously writes to PostgreSQL (secondary). Reads still come from MongoDB. If PG write fails, log the failure and let CDC catch up — do not fail the user request. Phase 3 (Dual-Read): Order Service writes to both. Reads come from PostgreSQL as primary, with async shadow-reads from MongoDB for comparison. Consistency Verifier runs continuously. Phase 4 (Cutover): PostgreSQL becomes sole primary. MongoDB writes stop. MongoDB kept read-only for 2 weeks as safety net before decommissioning.","patterns_used":[{"pattern":"Strangler Fig","rationale":"Incrementally replaces MongoDB with PostgreSQL without big-bang cutover. Each phase moves more responsibility to PostgreSQL while keeping MongoDB as fallback."},{"pattern":"Change Data Capture (CDC)","rationale":"Ensures no writes are lost during the backfill window. The oplog tail captures all mutations and replays them idempotently to PostgreSQL."},{"pattern":"Repository Pattern with Strategy","rationale":"Both MongoDB and PostgreSQL implementations share the same OrderRepository interface. The active implementation is selected by the feature flag, enabling zero-code-change cutover and rollback."},{"pattern":"Feature Flag Phased Rollout","rationale":"Migration phases are controlled by configuration, not deployments. Rollback is instant — flip the flag back to MONGO_PRIMARY."},{"pattern":"Idempotent Writes","rationale":"All writes to PostgreSQL during migration use upsert semantics keyed on order_id + version. Safe to replay CDC events or re-run backfill batches."},{"pattern":"Shadow Read Verification","rationale":"During dual-read phase, reads from both databases are compared asynchronously to build confidence before cutover."}]},"domain_model":{"bounded_contexts":[{"name":"Order Management","classification":"core","aggregates":["Order (root: order_id, contains OrderItems, ShippingInfo, OrderStatus lifecycle)","Payment (root: payment_id, linked to order_id, contains PaymentAttempts, RefundRecords)"]},{"name":"Migration Infrastructure","classification":"generic","aggregates":["MigrationState (root: migration_id, tracks phase, progress, verification stats)","ConsistencyReport (root: report_id, tracks sample comparisons and drift metrics)"]}],"context_map":[{"upstream":"Order Management","downstream":"Migration Infrastructure","relationship":"Conformist — Migration Infrastructure conforms to Order Management's model. It reads and transforms order data but never dictates schema changes to the Order domain."}]},"trade_offs":[{"decision":"Dual-write with CDC backfill instead of CDC-only migration","gains":"Stronger consistency guarantee during steady-state. Once dual-write is active, PostgreSQL gets writes synchronously — no replication lag. Simpler to reason about correctness.","sacrifices":"Slightly more complex application code during the dual-write phase. Small latency increase (~2-5ms) per write due to second database call.","alternatives_considered":["CDC-only migration (simpler app code but introduces replication lag and makes consistency verification harder)","Blue-green database cutover (requires downtime or extremely tight coordination window)","Application-level event sourcing replay (too invasive — requires rewriting the write path)"]},{"decision":"MongoDB write failure in dual-write phase is non-blocking for PG failures (not vice versa)","gains":"User-facing operations never fail due to the migration target being unhealthy. Production stability is preserved.","sacrifices":"Brief inconsistency window if PG write fails — CDC catches up, but there's a small lag. Requires monitoring.","alternatives_considered":["Fail both if either fails (too risky — PG issues would cause production outage)","Async-only PG writes via queue (adds infrastructure complexity, harder to verify consistency)"]},{"decision":"Relational schema with normalized tables rather than JSONB document storage in PostgreSQL","gains":"Full benefit of ACID transactions, foreign key constraints, efficient joins for reporting — the stated migration goals.","sacrifices":"Requires careful document-to-relational mapping. Flexible/dynamic fields in MongoDB documents need a migration strategy (dedicated columns, or a controlled JSONB overflow column for truly dynamic data).","alternatives_considered":["JSONB-primary storage in PostgreSQL (easier migration but defeats the purpose of moving to a relational database)","Hybrid: normalized core fields + JSONB for extensions (good compromise if some fields are truly dynamic)"]},{"decision":"Keep MongoDB read-only for 2 weeks post-cutover before decommissioning","gains":"Safety net for rollback. If a subtle data issue is discovered post-cutover, can revert to MongoDB as primary within minutes.","sacrifices":"Operational cost of running both databases for 2 extra weeks. Team must resist the temptation to skip verification and decommission early.","alternatives_considered":["Immediate decommission (too risky)","30-day retention (excessive cost, 2 weeks is sufficient given continuous verification)"]}],"flexibility_points":[{"area":"Migration phase progression","evolution_path":"Feature flags allow moving forward and backward between phases without deployments. If issues arise at any phase, instant rollback to the previous phase."},{"area":"Repository interface","evolution_path":"The shared OrderRepository interface means the application layer is database-agnostic. Post-migration, if requirements change, swapping storage again would follow the same pattern."},{"area":"Backfill parallelism and rate limiting","evolution_path":"Backfill Worker's batch size and concurrency are configurable. Can be tuned based on observed production impact — start conservative (2 workers, 1000 batch) and increase."},{"area":"Schema evolution","evolution_path":"PostgreSQL schema uses explicit migrations (e.g., Flyway/Liquibase). Adding columns, indexes, or constraints post-migration follows standard relational migration practices — much more predictable than MongoDB schema drift."}],"rigidity_points":[{"area":"Document-to-relational mapping","reason":"The transformation logic from MongoDB documents to PostgreSQL relational rows must be defined precisely and cannot change mid-migration without restarting the backfill. This mapping is the single most critical piece of correctness."},{"area":"Order ID consistency","reason":"order_id must be the same value in both databases. If MongoDB uses ObjectId, the PostgreSQL schema must either use the same string representation or maintain a deterministic mapping. Changing this mid-migration would be catastrophic."},{"area":"Migration phase ordering","reason":"Phases must progress in order: Backfill → Dual-Write → Dual-Read → Cutover. Skipping phases risks data loss or inconsistency. The orchestrator enforces this."}],"risks":[{"risk":"Document-to-relational mapping errors — MongoDB documents may have inconsistent shapes, missing fields, or nested structures that don't map cleanly to relational tables","severity":"critical","mitigation":"Run a pre-migration analysis job that scans all 8M documents and catalogs every unique field path, type, and null rate. Use this to design the relational schema with full knowledge of the actual data. Build transformation unit tests covering every discovered document variant."},{"risk":"CDC oplog lag during high-traffic periods causing consistency drift during backfill phase","severity":"high","mitigation":"Monitor CDC lag metric continuously. If lag exceeds 30 seconds, pause the backfill worker to let CDC catch up. Set alerts at 10-second lag threshold."},{"risk":"Dual-write phase adds latency to the critical order creation path","severity":"medium","mitigation":"Measure P99 latency before and during dual-write. At 200 writes/min (~3.3/sec), the additional PG write adds ~2-5ms. If latency is unacceptable, fall back to async PG writes via a local queue with CDC as backup consistency mechanism."},{"risk":"Hidden application code that queries MongoDB directly, bypassing the repository layer","severity":"high","mitigation":"Grep the entire codebase for direct MongoDB collection references outside the repository. Audit all database connection usages. Add a MongoDB query proxy/wrapper that logs all queries during migration to detect rogue access patterns."},{"risk":"Backfill takes longer than expected, extending the risky dual-operation window","severity":"medium","mitigation":"Estimate: 8M records at 1000/batch = 8000 batches. At 2 batches/sec with 2 workers = ~33 minutes for raw transfer. With transformation overhead and rate limiting, budget 2-4 hours. Run a dry-run against a staging copy of production data to get actual timing."},{"risk":"Rollback from PG-primary back to MongoDB-primary loses writes that only went to PG","severity":"high","mitigation":"During dual-write and dual-read phases, MongoDB always receives writes. Only in the final cutover phase does MongoDB stop receiving writes. Rollback from cutover phase requires replaying PG writes back to MongoDB — build this reverse-sync capability before entering cutover."}],"implementation_guidance":{"recommended_approach":"Implement in 4 sequential phases, each gated by verification criteria. Start with the PostgreSQL schema design and repository implementation (can be developed and tested independently). Then build the backfill and CDC infrastructure. Only enable dual-write in production once all components are thoroughly tested in staging with a copy of production data.

